Breakouts

Home  >  2020 Ultimate Draft Kit  >  UDK – Expert Lists – Breakouts

Our Expert Breakout Picks for the Upcoming Season

Below are some of our favorite breakout candidates for the upcoming fantasy football season. What exactly is a breakout? A breakout is a fantasy player that is primed to become a fantasy darling. A fantasy superstar. A fantasy game-changer. These are players who flashed, showed signs of success, and with another year under their belt might just surprise you with incredible seasons.

Quarterbacks

Kyler Murray, ARI

Each of the last few years we've seen a player emerge from a quality fantasy quarterback to a fantasy superstar. Murray's opportunity is before him, as the team has improved the offensive line and brought in arguably the best wide receiver in the NFL in DeAndre Hopkins. Murray gives fantasy owners a huge baseline with his rushing numbers, and last year the Cardinals converted so rarely inside the red zone that his fantasy numbers were deflated significantly. If his touchdown % can increase (likely with the addition of Hopkins and the return of Kenyan Drake) then Murray is primed for a breakout 2020.

Josh Allen, BUF

Much like Kyler Murray, Allen has an opportunity to improve upon his rushing baseline due to elite WR talent being added to the offense. Stefon Diggs is one of the NFL's best at getting open deep, and Allen boasts one of the biggest arms in the NFL. Connecting more regularly with his WR will inflate the rushing baseline Allen brings to the table, and hopefully give fantasy owners more week-winning performances in 2020. A breakout is coming as the Bills vie for a now possible division title.

Running Backs

Josh Jacobs, LV

Josh Jacobs is a three-down back that simply did not receive the level of pass-game work fantasy owners hoped for last year. In 2020 look for him to be even more involved and add to his elite rookie year production. Coming off an injury-laden 242/1150/7 campaign, Jacobs will be the centerpiece of a viable Oakland offense. He's everything you want in an emerging feature back.

Kenyan Drake, ARI

Need a refresher on how good Kenyan Drake was once he arrived in Arizona last season? He was the RB4 from week 9 on, a perfect fit for the Kliff Kingsburg/Kyler Murray offense. He returns on a new contract for 2020 and slides right into the emerging offense as a dual threat RB. He's simply not being drafted near his ceiling right now and has breakout potential in 2020 in an offense that boasts a near league leading plays-per-game total.

Miles Sanders, PHI

Miles Sanders broke out to end the 2019 season, and fantasy owners are left holding their breath when it comes to 2020. Will the Eagles add another RB? Will the team be willing to give Miles a feature role? This team invested it's highest draft capital on Sanders since LeSean McCoy was drafted, and Miles delivered to end the year. If the backfield depth chart stays status quo, it should be a big year for Sanders in 2020, who was the RB8 from Week 12 on last year.

Wide Receivers

Calvin Ridley, ATL

If there's one player that all three guys seem to be "in" on this year, it's Calvin Ridley. Austin Hooper is gone, Mohamed Sanu is gone, Davonta Freeman is gone. Ridley enters his year three breakout season looking like this year's Chris Godwin. With 17 touchdowns in his first two years, Ridley has a knack for big plays and should have plenty of opportunities for his first 1000 yard season in 2020. While Julio is the lead dog of the offense, Ridley could push for "best value" in terms of average draft position and fantasy production.

Marquise Brown, BAL

A big play machine, the question marks surrounding Hollywood Brown will all circle around his opportunity in the offense. A hyper-talented speed demon, Brown will need to stay healthy and receive consistent targets from Lamar Jackson to evolve and breakout in 2020. He represents a higher risk, high reward breakout candidate who could emerge as a Tyreek Hill like value if given the opportunity.

Terry McLaurin, WAS

Andy will have no part in this breakout prediction, but both Jason and Mike love the opportunity McLaurin has moving into year two. While Haskins is an issue, McLaurin proved that consistent QB play was no stumbling block for him in 2019, delivering several highly meaningful performances for fantasy owners. If Haskins can take a step forward, Terry McLaurin looks like the clear cut WR1 on this team and will have every opportunity to prove it.

Tight Ends

Evan Engram, NYG

The only thing that stands between Evan Engram and fantasy glory is Evan Engram. An elite big-play tight end, Engram has dealt with consistent injury issues throughout his playing days thus far. Despite this, he remains as a breakout candidate for 2020 due to the sheer pace he maintains when active and on the field. Much like George Kittle in San Francisco, Engram can score from anywhere on the field and is a quarterback's best friend. It all comes down to health, but Mike in particular is banking on Engram bouncing back in a big way in 2020.

Noah Fant, DEN

Consider this one an Andy special. While Jason and Mike saw the upside of Noah Fant last year, it's Andy who's calling for the breakout season in 2020. Fant was the 20th overall pick in the first round last year, a dynamic pass catcher who showed he can turn a small reception into a big gain in a hurry. Coming into year two, Fant should take another big step forward as a focal point of a rebuilt offense in Denver. Don't sleep on a year two breakout from Noah Fant.

Mike Gesicki, MIA

It took a while but we finally saw the ability and talent of Mike Gesicki over the back half of 2019. From week 9 on, Gesicki was the tight end #7 on the year, and closed the season on fire. The former #42 overall pick from Penn State, Gesicki emerged and looks to capitalize on the great finish with a solid 2020 campaign. There are a handful of tight ends each year with both the talent and opportunity to break out, and Gesicki fits that mold in 2020.
